Beijing — China's economy surprised many by slowing in the second quarter of this year.
Similarly unexpected is that most of the data released since July indicates that China's growth has stabilized.
As expected, the market let out a collective sigh of relief.
But should investors continue to remain tense?
The most serious problem facing Chinese authorities at present is excess capacity.
For example, China's annual steel production capacity is ten billion tons, but the total production in 2012 was only 7.2 billion tons — representing an utilization rate of 72%.
More notably, the steel industry's profit margin was only 0.04% in 2012.
In fact, the profit obtained per ton of production can only buy a lollipop.
So far this year, the average profit margin of China's top 500 companies is 4.34%, down by 33 basis points from 2012.
Some say that today's overcapacity stems from excessive investment in the past.
Some people also believe that overcapacity is due to insufficient effective demand.
The government's viewpoint seems to be a compromise between the two.
On one hand, authorities are asking thousands of companies to reduce their production capacity.
On the other hand, the government introduced some "mini-stimulus" measures, such as exempting micro-enterprises from value-added tax and business tax, and requiring banks to increase loans to export-oriented enterprises.
The official line from the authorities is that China's growth model needs to reduce investment and increase consumption.
But not all Chinese economists agree with this.
They认为 capital stock is a key factor in growth, and China's per capita capital stock remains relatively low compared to developed countries, which means there is significant room for future investment.
Indeed, capital accumulation is a major driver of economic growth, and catching up to the income levels of developed countries requires China to increase its capital stock over the long term.
But what matters is not the scale of the capital stock, nor even the level of investment; it is the growth rate of investment, which has been significantly higher than the GDP growth rate for decades.
According to official statistics, China's investment rate has approached 50% of GDP.
Thanks to the absorption constraint, capital efficiency decreases steadily as the size of capital increases.
If the environmental damage caused by rapidly growing investment is taken into account, China's capital efficiency would be even lower.
The role of human capital and technological progress in economic growth is no less significant than that of physical capital and labor.
If resource allocation tilts towards physical capital at the expense of undermining human capital accumulation – which is an indispensable condition for adequate consumption – economic growth is more likely to slow down rather than accelerate.
Therefore, China should lower the growth rate of investment and raise the growth rate of consumption, stabilizing the investment rate at a more sustainable level.
Of course, it is not entirely wrong to say that China's excess capacity reflects a deficiency in effective demand.
But where does effective demand come from?
In this regard, China's steel industry once again provides a good example.
Despite China lacking comparative advantage in steel production, it still built approximately one thousand steel mills, accounting for half of the global total output.
As early as 2004, the Chinese government tried to cool down overinvestment; however, strong demand from infrastructure investment and real estate development kept output growing rapidly, rising from 3 hundred million tons that year to 1 billion tons by 2012.
Investment in China can be roughly divided into three categories: manufacturing, infrastructure, and real estate.
At the end of 2008 and throughout 2009, when the global financial crisis was at its peak, infrastructure investments spurred by economic stimulus packages sustained output growth.
In 2010, real estate development investment supplanted infrastructure investment as the main driver of growth.
Now, infrastructure and real estate are important drivers of China's growth.
China indeed needs more infrastructure investment - particularly in electricity and hydropower, transportation, and communications.
But the investment pace must take adequate account of financial constraints.
More importantly, China can and should invest more in social infrastructure such as schools, hospitals, and nursing homes.
But real estate investment is a different matter.
It is difficult to judge the severity of China's real estate bubble and when it will burst.
But one thing is certain: China has already invested too much in real estate development.
The per capita income in China is under $6,000, but the homeownership rate in China is as high as around 90%, while it is less than 70% in the United States.
The per capita housing area is 32.9 square meters, while the median household housing area in Hong Kong has just reached 48 square meters.
There are 696 five-star hotels in China, with an additional 500 under construction.
Five of the ten tallest under construction are in China.
In my opinion, this can only be described as madness.
The Chinese economy is being hostage to real estate investment.
On the one hand, China should not address overcapacity by maintaining high growth rates in real estate investment.
Social housing projects investments are welcome, but real estate investments currently accounting for as high as 10-13% of GDP are already too high.
On the other hand, if the growth in real estate investment slows down, overcapacity cannot be eliminated.
This highlights the structural adjustment challenges that China faces—challenges that should also keep investors cautious.
In summary, two points are worth noting.
First, unlike other investment types, real estate investment does not increase the stock of productive capital.
There is no fundamental difference between houses and high-end durable consumer goods.
Secondly, in China's statistical data, the growth rate of total fixed asset investment is significantly higher than the growth rate of total capital formation.
This indicates that the data on the growth rate of fixed investment may overstate the speed of accumulation of capital stock.
Therefore, while the Chinese government should definitely reduce its reliance on investment for economic growth, the actions must be very cautious.
